Use `clingo file1 file2 ... ` to find answers, for example, `clingo normal.lp ring.lp branch.lp` can help you create a mission graph with cycles and neat alternative paths.

Use `clingo file1 file2 ... -V0 --out-atomf=%s. | head -n 1 | clingo - file 3 ...` to find answers based on the result from `clingo file1 file2 ... `, for example, `clingo normal.lp ring.lp branch.lp -V0 --out-atomf=%s. | head -n 1 | layout.lp -V0 --out-atomf=%s. | head -n 1 | clingo - space.lp decoration.lp` can help you create a dungeon with monsters and treasures based on the mission graph, and in most cases it is faster than directly using `clingo file1 file2 ... ` to generate everything.

Reference: [clingo](https://potassco.org/clingo/)

Example: ![dungeon layout](data:image/png;base64,)

Notes: In the picture above, the red zones refer to monster (patrol) areas, blue tiles are treasures, orange zones are lava fields and the navy blue tiles are traps. The generator simply randomly places monsters, treasures, lava fields, and traps in "corridors," leaving the design of special mission rooms to human designers.
